1
00:00:12,945 --> 00:00:15,080
I'm going to work
in Woolworth's.

2
00:00:15,082 --> 00:00:18,016
When I grow up, I want
to be an astronaut.

3
00:00:18,018 --> 00:00:20,385
When I get married, I would
like to have two children.

4
00:00:20,387 --> 00:00:23,822
My heart's desire is
to see my daddy.

5
00:00:23,824 --> 00:00:26,858
I don't want to answer that.

6
00:00:29,361 --> 00:00:31,729
(narrator) This is no ordinary
outing to the zoo.

7
00:00:31,731 --> 00:00:34,866
It's a very special occasion.

8
00:00:34,868 --> 00:00:37,002
We've brought these children
together for the very first time.

9
00:00:37,004 --> 00:00:39,371
(screaming)

10
00:00:39,373 --> 00:00:41,906
They're like any other children,
except that they come

11
00:00:41,908 --> 00:00:44,609
from startlingly different
backgrounds.

12
00:00:44,611 --> 00:00:46,812
Stop it at once.

13
00:00:46,814 --> 00:00:50,681
We've brought these children together
because we wanted a glimpse of England

14
00:00:50,683 --> 00:00:53,184
in the year 2000.

15
00:00:53,186 --> 00:00:56,454
The shop steward and the
executive of the year 2000

16
00:00:56,456 --> 00:00:58,890
are now seven years old.

17
00:01:02,428 --> 00:01:05,763
(Michael Apted) In 1964,
World In Action made "Seven up!"

18
00:01:05,765 --> 00:01:10,602
and we've been back to film
these children every seven years.

19
00:01:12,071 --> 00:01:14,406
They are now 49.

20
00:01:18,644 --> 00:01:22,113
Is it important to fight? Yes.

21
00:01:23,549 --> 00:01:28,286
Tony was brought up
in the East End of London.

22
00:01:28,288 --> 00:01:30,288
Want to be a jockey
when I grow up.

23
00:01:30,290 --> 00:01:33,225
Yeah, I want to be a jockey
when I grow up.

24
00:01:35,427 --> 00:01:38,363
At 14, he was already
an apprentice

25
00:01:38,365 --> 00:01:41,566
at Tommy Gosling's
racing stable at Epsom.

26
00:01:41,568 --> 00:01:44,402
At 15, he'd left school.

27
00:01:48,740 --> 00:01:51,743
This is a photo finish,
when I rode at Newbury.

28
00:01:51,745 --> 00:01:53,744
I'm the one with the white cap.

29
00:01:53,746 --> 00:01:55,780
I was beaten a length
and a half off third,

30
00:01:55,782 --> 00:01:58,182
and I had a photo finish.

31
00:01:58,184 --> 00:02:00,251
(Michael) Do you
regret not making it?

32
00:02:00,253 --> 00:02:03,855
I would have given my right arm
at the time to become a jockey,

33
00:02:03,857 --> 00:02:05,757
but now...

34
00:02:05,759 --> 00:02:08,093
Well, I wasn't good enough.

35
00:02:08,095 --> 00:02:10,928
(Michael) What will you do if
you don't make it as a jockey?

36
00:02:10,930 --> 00:02:12,297
I don't know.

37
00:02:12,299 --> 00:02:16,000
If I knew I couldn't be one,
I'd get out of the game.

38
00:02:16,002 --> 00:02:18,336
Wouldn't bother.

39
00:02:18,338 --> 00:02:21,106
What do you think
you would do then?

40
00:02:21,108 --> 00:02:22,841
Learn on taxis.

41
00:02:22,843 --> 00:02:27,144
At 21, he was
on the knowledge,

42
00:02:27,146 --> 00:02:30,849
and by 28, he owned his own cab.

43
00:02:30,851 --> 00:02:33,251
It's surprising who
you pick up, you see.

44
00:02:33,253 --> 00:02:36,454
I once met Kojak.
I picked him up.

45
00:02:36,456 --> 00:02:39,858
And Warren Mitchell,
Alf Garnett, you know.

46
00:02:39,860 --> 00:02:42,593
Have you got a girlfriend?
No.

47
00:02:42,595 --> 00:02:45,029
Would you like to have
a girlfriend?

48
00:02:45,031 --> 00:02:46,497
No.

49
00:02:46,499 --> 00:02:48,199
You understand four F's?

50
00:02:48,201 --> 00:02:50,368
Find 'em, feed 'em
and forget 'em.

51
00:02:50,370 --> 00:02:53,337
The other "F" - I'll let you
use your own discriminish.

52
00:02:53,339 --> 00:02:57,742
I mean, this one
I tried to do the 3 F's,

53
00:02:57,744 --> 00:03:00,111
but I couldn't forget her.

54
00:03:00,113 --> 00:03:02,747
I went to a discothèque.

55
00:03:02,749 --> 00:03:04,849
He was in the pub earlier on,

56
00:03:04,851 --> 00:03:07,552
and afterwards we
went to a discothèque.

57
00:03:07,554 --> 00:03:09,955
And Tony was standing there,
and I just -

58
00:03:09,957 --> 00:03:13,058
From there, I just - that was it.

59
00:03:13,060 --> 00:03:14,993
(laughs)

60
00:03:14,995 --> 00:03:18,062
Couldn't get rid of him.
(laughs)

61
00:03:18,064 --> 00:03:22,033
We have our ups and downs.
No more than anyone else.

62
00:03:22,035 --> 00:03:25,570
I think you gotta work
at a marriage.

63
00:03:25,572 --> 00:03:28,640
I think all marriages
go through stages.

64
00:03:28,642 --> 00:03:31,376
You can't stand each other.
You go through, you know -

65
00:03:31,378 --> 00:03:35,647
I think, "Oh, god, I hate him.
I wish he'd get out." I do.

66
00:03:35,649 --> 00:03:37,815
We've been to the
edge of the cliff

67
00:03:37,817 --> 00:03:39,817
and looked over
a couple of times,

68
00:03:39,819 --> 00:03:43,955
and we've always seemed
to sort of go back,

69
00:03:43,957 --> 00:03:46,458
and we've sort of
stayed the course.

70
00:03:46,460 --> 00:03:50,628
But I must say - I mean,
it's not easy being married.

71
00:03:50,630 --> 00:03:54,532
By 42, Tony and Debbie
had left the East End

72
00:03:54,534 --> 00:03:57,435
and moved to Woodford in Essex.

73
00:03:57,437 --> 00:04:01,673
We were going to put a conservatory
here, but if you look along here,

74
00:04:01,675 --> 00:04:04,074
we put a patio in and
the pond for the fish,

75
00:04:04,076 --> 00:04:06,477
but the only thing I ever done

76
00:04:06,479 --> 00:04:09,447
was I planted them three trees.

77
00:04:09,449 --> 00:04:11,549
Well, since you was
last here, Michael...

78
00:04:11,551 --> 00:04:13,651
We had small trees,
if you remember.

79
00:04:13,653 --> 00:04:17,588
Now they've sort of grown a bit.

80
00:04:17,590 --> 00:04:20,091
(Michael) So why
are the trees singed?

81
00:04:20,093 --> 00:04:23,561
We was burning some
Rubbish at the back

82
00:04:23,563 --> 00:04:26,564
and set light to the tree,
and there we all were,

83
00:04:26,566 --> 00:04:30,034
sort of like throwing
all buckets of water over it,

84
00:04:30,036 --> 00:04:32,269
and sadly enough,
it singed the tree.

85
00:04:46,719 --> 00:04:49,854
At 49, they've taken out a second
mortgage on the London house

86
00:04:49,856 --> 00:04:54,125
and sunk the money in
a holiday home in Spain.

87
00:04:54,127 --> 00:04:56,294
I'm very pleased with the house.

88
00:04:56,296 --> 00:04:59,331
I said the progress we made in the
little space of time that we've had

89
00:04:59,333 --> 00:05:01,499
to work here and get it
all sort of shipshape

90
00:05:01,501 --> 00:05:03,334
I think is done, really,

91
00:05:03,336 --> 00:05:06,170
to the testament
of my wife Debbie.

92
00:05:06,172 --> 00:05:07,672
As per usual.

93
00:05:07,674 --> 00:05:09,407
(Michael laughs)

94
00:05:09,409 --> 00:05:11,509
(Tony) Debbie went
to the furniture shop,

95
00:05:11,511 --> 00:05:13,978
and she sort of picked
all the furniture.

96
00:05:13,980 --> 00:05:17,682
All what you see is all
Debbie's choice of furniture

97
00:05:17,684 --> 00:05:20,118
and her, really, sort of style.

98
00:05:20,120 --> 00:05:21,653
The floor -

99
00:05:21,655 --> 00:05:25,390
We were led to believe
that we had a choice of tiling,

100
00:05:25,392 --> 00:05:28,393
whether it's a light beige
or, you know, light brown.

101
00:05:28,395 --> 00:05:31,395
That's the first I've heard
that we had a choice,

102
00:05:31,397 --> 00:05:33,230
'cause I would have had plain.

103
00:05:33,232 --> 00:05:36,067
I've just gone into the neighbours'
house, and they've got all plain.

104
00:05:36,069 --> 00:05:38,069
Well, there you go.
I never got told that.

105
00:05:38,071 --> 00:05:41,072
He said it was a choice that we
had when we suggested to buy it,

106
00:05:41,074 --> 00:05:43,407
so that was where
the mistake was made.

107
00:05:43,409 --> 00:05:45,510
Because you don't listen.
Say that again.

108
00:05:45,512 --> 00:05:48,646
You don't listen.
Can't hear you. (laughs)

109
00:05:48,648 --> 00:05:52,684
Tony and Debbie still
work as London cabbies.

110
00:05:52,686 --> 00:05:56,354
We sold our cabs because we are
going to spend more time out here.

111
00:05:56,356 --> 00:05:59,090
So it's not really conducive
to own a cab, is it?

112
00:05:59,092 --> 00:06:02,594
Because the cab will be left
out on the drive or, you know -

113
00:06:02,596 --> 00:06:07,498
It's pointless, so we just
hired a cab independently now.

114
00:06:07,500 --> 00:06:11,903
I'm working harder now
than I really ever have done,

115
00:06:11,905 --> 00:06:15,573
but I feel that
it's for something.

116
00:06:15,575 --> 00:06:18,108
Son, why do you want to be
a cab driver for, mate?

117
00:06:18,110 --> 00:06:20,211
All the holidays in Spain
every year...

118
00:06:20,213 --> 00:06:22,547
But, son, it's hard work out there.
You're not reaching me yet.

119
00:06:22,549 --> 00:06:24,883
Not getting to you. No, you're
not getting to me. All right?

120
00:06:24,885 --> 00:06:27,217
Now be bigger.
Dominate me, all right? Son...

121
00:06:27,219 --> 00:06:30,455
At 28, Tony was taking
acting lessons.

122
00:06:30,457 --> 00:06:34,391
Now he supplements his income
with occasional TV jobs.

123
00:06:34,393 --> 00:06:36,393
(Tony) Oi!

124
00:06:36,395 --> 00:06:38,395
That's all I got on me.

125
00:06:38,397 --> 00:06:41,666
Mate, if I had a pound for every time
I've heard that, I'd be a rich man.

126
00:06:41,668 --> 00:06:44,568
Get him!

127
00:06:44,570 --> 00:06:47,471
A guy contacted me
from my agency,

128
00:06:47,473 --> 00:06:49,773
from my acting agency,
and I got in touch with him.

129
00:06:49,775 --> 00:06:55,646
And he writes plays, and he's
been inspired by your up programs,

130
00:06:55,648 --> 00:06:58,682
which go all round the world,
and he saw it.

131
00:06:58,684 --> 00:07:03,054
And we got together
and we wrote a biographical play

132
00:07:03,056 --> 00:07:05,857
all about my life story.

133
00:07:05,859 --> 00:07:09,494
We took one of these episodes over to
New York and done it on a play reading.

134
00:07:09,496 --> 00:07:12,997
And I got up, playing
the lead role, you know,

135
00:07:12,999 --> 00:07:16,233
and it just blew the roof off.

136
00:07:16,235 --> 00:07:21,205
And we're looking for someone to
pick it up and put it on stage.

137
00:07:21,207 --> 00:07:24,442
(woman) Would everybody please sit
round now, get on with their work?

138
00:07:24,444 --> 00:07:27,345
I don't want to see
any backs to me.

139
00:07:27,347 --> 00:07:29,447
Shouldn't be anybody
turning round.

140
00:07:29,449 --> 00:07:32,650
Tony, do you hear as well?

141
00:07:32,652 --> 00:07:37,622
Get on with your work
at the front.

142
00:07:37,624 --> 00:07:40,090
Tony!
Don't turn round again.

143
00:07:40,092 --> 00:07:42,760
There's only one ambition,
and, really, I want a baby son.

144
00:07:42,762 --> 00:07:45,596
If I see my baby son, that will
be my ambition fulfilled.

145
00:07:45,598 --> 00:07:48,566
No one knows that.
Only you know.

146
00:07:48,568 --> 00:07:50,968
Debbie and Tony
have three children -

147
00:07:50,970 --> 00:07:57,175
Nicky, Jody and Perri.

148
00:07:57,177 --> 00:08:00,077
Nicky's doing quite well.
He's still a French polisher.

149
00:08:00,079 --> 00:08:02,546
It's an old-time profession,
as you know.

150
00:08:02,548 --> 00:08:04,549
He's working for a firm,

151
00:08:04,551 --> 00:08:06,751
and he's very happy
in his work, isn't he?

152
00:08:06,753 --> 00:08:11,088
He's been brought up
very respectful to people,

153
00:08:11,090 --> 00:08:13,090
very well-mannered person,

154
00:08:13,092 --> 00:08:16,894
He's a hard worker.

155
00:08:16,896 --> 00:08:19,397
Jody, I mean,
at this present time,

156
00:08:19,399 --> 00:08:25,603
she's just - relies on us
a great deal, and...

157
00:08:25,605 --> 00:08:30,875
She's been very scarred with
a relationship that she was in.

158
00:08:30,877 --> 00:08:33,711
Her relationship with her
first love of her own life

159
00:08:33,713 --> 00:08:36,480
was very turbulent,

160
00:08:36,482 --> 00:08:40,251
but he's the father of her kid.

161
00:08:40,253 --> 00:08:43,487
We're going to make sure
she gets through it.

162
00:08:43,489 --> 00:08:46,624
And it's been quite a
strain on Debbie and I

163
00:08:46,626 --> 00:08:49,627
to see her in that
sort of situation.

164
00:08:49,629 --> 00:08:51,995
I'm very proud of Perri as well.

165
00:08:51,997 --> 00:08:54,999
She got in the post office,
and that's what's she doing.

166
00:08:55,001 --> 00:08:57,868
Postman Pel.
That's our postman Pel.

167
00:08:57,870 --> 00:08:59,570
She loves it, you know.
She works hard.

168
00:08:59,572 --> 00:09:02,306
She's up at four
in the morning.

169
00:09:02,308 --> 00:09:04,075
She's got a lovely boyfriend.

170
00:09:04,077 --> 00:09:06,177
He loves her more
than you can imagine,

171
00:09:06,179 --> 00:09:08,879
and he's certainly
got my blessing.

172
00:09:08,881 --> 00:09:11,549
Big lad, very nice guy,
loves his football.

173
00:09:11,551 --> 00:09:14,485
You know, typical East End kid.

174
00:09:14,487 --> 00:09:16,854
Go. Aah!

175
00:09:16,856 --> 00:09:19,390
Head up, son.
That's too quick.

176
00:09:19,392 --> 00:09:21,526
We are the backbone
for the kids, aren't we?

177
00:09:21,528 --> 00:09:24,462
Yeah, but I think your parents
are anyway, you know.

178
00:09:24,464 --> 00:09:25,996
Your parents are -

179
00:09:25,998 --> 00:09:29,700
You never visualize anything ever
happening to your parents, do you?

180
00:09:29,702 --> 00:09:33,370
You think they are there forever.

181
00:09:33,372 --> 00:09:36,673
Toni's five, Harry's
four, nearly five,

182
00:09:36,675 --> 00:09:39,443
and little Pru, she's nearly two.

183
00:09:39,445 --> 00:09:42,279
No, three.
She's three.

184
00:09:42,281 --> 00:09:45,617
I'm an hands-on granddad.

185
00:09:45,619 --> 00:09:48,919
I love my grandchildren
more, if you can imagine,

186
00:09:48,921 --> 00:09:51,755
I'd say not my own kids,
but in a different way.

187
00:09:51,757 --> 00:09:56,027
It's an obsession
of love, you know.

188
00:09:56,029 --> 00:10:00,565
You see these grandchildren,
and they're part of you.

189
00:10:00,567 --> 00:10:02,733
No, granddad. No.

190
00:10:02,735 --> 00:10:05,402
They're hard work at times.

191
00:10:05,404 --> 00:10:07,405
We don't mind, though,
Michael. I mean -

192
00:10:07,407 --> 00:10:09,807
'cause you slow down and you don't
realize you're slowing down.

193
00:10:09,809 --> 00:10:11,976
All I understand is dogs' prices,

194
00:10:11,978 --> 00:10:15,146
girls, knowledge,
roads, streets, squares

195
00:10:15,148 --> 00:10:17,281
and mum and dad and love.

196
00:10:17,283 --> 00:10:19,516
That's all I understand,
that's all I want to understand.

197
00:10:19,518 --> 00:10:21,986
By the time he was 35,

198
00:10:21,988 --> 00:10:25,489
both Tony's parents had died.

199
00:10:25,491 --> 00:10:29,059
I'm at the graveside.
I'm talking to her, little things.

200
00:10:29,061 --> 00:10:31,061
I've got all images
running through me mind,

201
00:10:31,063 --> 00:10:33,597
sayin' like, "Tony, go downstairs,
get me fine weights."

202
00:10:33,599 --> 00:10:35,166
You know, "one and a penny."

203
00:10:35,168 --> 00:10:37,468
And I used to go in the shop.

204
00:10:37,470 --> 00:10:39,903
She used to throw the cotton
in an hair curler

205
00:10:39,905 --> 00:10:41,905
over the landing,

206
00:10:41,907 --> 00:10:45,876
and I used to tie the cigarettes
on this bit of cotton.

207
00:10:45,878 --> 00:10:47,878
She used to pull 'em up,
and she goes -

208
00:10:47,880 --> 00:10:49,713
See her in the end -
(inhales)

209
00:10:49,715 --> 00:10:53,116
"Thanks, Tone. See you
after school. Be good."

210
00:10:53,118 --> 00:10:55,453
And that's the way it was.

211
00:10:55,455 --> 00:10:57,822
We knew my dad
was terminally ill,

212
00:10:57,824 --> 00:10:59,490
although having said that,

213
00:10:59,492 --> 00:11:02,526
still didn't make it
any easier for us.

214
00:11:02,528 --> 00:11:07,064
When my dad died,
I took it really hard.

215
00:11:07,066 --> 00:11:08,799
I can't.

216
00:11:12,371 --> 00:11:17,841
Nellie Rose is - my mum,
'cause her name is Nell,

217
00:11:17,843 --> 00:11:19,844
and her mother's name's Rose,

218
00:11:19,846 --> 00:11:22,679
so my Jody and all the family

219
00:11:22,681 --> 00:11:25,616
were conjuring up some names
that we could name it.

220
00:11:25,618 --> 00:11:28,652
Jody at the finish
said "Nellie Rose",

221
00:11:28,654 --> 00:11:30,154
the name of our mums.

222
00:11:31,757 --> 00:11:35,326
Sometimes on a Saturday morning
I go to the pictures,

223
00:11:35,328 --> 00:11:39,063
sometimes with my friends
and sometimes with him.

224
00:11:39,065 --> 00:11:41,298
You don't.
I do.

225
00:11:41,300 --> 00:11:43,567
She don't.

226
00:11:43,569 --> 00:11:45,936
(Michael) And why did
you fall in love with him?

227
00:11:45,938 --> 00:11:47,304
Don't know.

228
00:11:47,306 --> 00:11:50,174
I don't know how you put up
with me for so long.

229
00:11:50,176 --> 00:11:53,210
I don't know how. Sometimes
I don't know how I stand him.

230
00:11:53,212 --> 00:11:55,413
Who's to say
in another ten years

231
00:11:55,415 --> 00:11:56,947
me and him might have split up.

232
00:11:56,949 --> 00:11:59,983
Quite possible, you know.
You don't know.

233
00:11:59,985 --> 00:12:03,754
When we filmed
Debbie and Tony at 42,

234
00:12:03,756 --> 00:12:06,357
the marriage seemed
to be in trouble.

235
00:12:06,359 --> 00:12:08,960
I'm not proud at all to say this,

236
00:12:08,962 --> 00:12:12,530
but situations arise that -

237
00:12:12,532 --> 00:12:16,833
I have - have had regretful
behaviour various times,

238
00:12:16,835 --> 00:12:18,902
but through...

239
00:12:18,904 --> 00:12:21,973
You got caught, and that was it.

240
00:12:21,975 --> 00:12:23,240
That's, you know -

241
00:12:23,242 --> 00:12:25,909
I'm not lying about
the fact, you know.

242
